WEBVTT

00:00:07.160 --> 00:00:09.250
PROFESSOR: Welcome back
to recitation.

00:00:09.250 --> 00:00:11.290
Today we're going to work
on a problem involving

00:00:11.290 --> 00:00:12.430
differential equations.

00:00:12.430 --> 00:00:15.030
I'm going to read it to you,
give you a little hint, give

00:00:15.030 --> 00:00:17.570
you some time to work on it, and
then I'll be back and work

00:00:17.570 --> 00:00:18.810
it out for you.

00:00:18.810 --> 00:00:23.030
So, the problem is to find a
function y equals f of x that

00:00:23.030 --> 00:00:26.790
has the following two
properties: d squared y dx

00:00:26.790 --> 00:00:28.400
squared is equal to 6x.

00:00:28.400 --> 00:00:30.410
And just to remind you what this
means, this is really,

00:00:30.410 --> 00:00:34.940
this is the second derivative
of y with respect to x.

00:00:34.940 --> 00:00:38.900
So, the second derivative with
respect to x should be 6x.

00:00:38.900 --> 00:00:42.340
And the second condition's kind
of long, but it says the

00:00:42.340 --> 00:00:46.450
graph of the function in the
xy plane passes through the

00:00:46.450 --> 00:00:49.880
point 1,1 with a horizontal
tangent there.

00:00:49.880 --> 00:00:51.240
So let me give you one hint.

00:00:51.240 --> 00:00:53.710
And that hint is that there are
some initial conditions

00:00:53.710 --> 00:00:54.420
buried in here.

00:00:54.420 --> 00:00:56.940
That's why we have
this condition.

00:00:56.940 --> 00:00:59.850
So I'm going to give you a
little bit of time to work on

00:00:59.850 --> 00:01:01.940
it and I'll be back and I'll
work it out with you.

00:01:10.530 --> 00:01:11.650
Welcome back.

00:01:11.650 --> 00:01:13.750
Hopefully you were able to start
at least solving the

00:01:13.750 --> 00:01:17.890
problem initially, give yourself
a little direction.

00:01:17.890 --> 00:01:20.460
So let's see how you did.

00:01:20.460 --> 00:01:24.770
OK, so the first thing I would
like to do is try and figure

00:01:24.770 --> 00:01:28.590
out maybe what the first
derivative of the function y

00:01:28.590 --> 00:01:29.490
equals f of x is.

00:01:29.490 --> 00:01:32.170
I have its second derivative, so
in order to find the first

00:01:32.170 --> 00:01:36.100
derivative I want to find,
ultimately a function that

00:01:36.100 --> 00:01:37.500
when I take its derivative
I get 6x.

00:01:37.500 --> 00:01:38.390
Right?

00:01:38.390 --> 00:01:40.530
So, we can think about this.

00:01:40.530 --> 00:01:43.720
Maybe the easiest thing for us
to do would actually be to

00:01:43.720 --> 00:01:47.600
consider another function
whose derivative is 6x.

00:01:47.600 --> 00:01:49.380
And we'll know that's dy dx.

00:01:49.380 --> 00:01:52.190
So I'm going to say
this: dy-- sorry--

00:01:52.190 --> 00:01:55.070
d squared y dx squared.

00:01:55.070 --> 00:01:58.050
I'm going to say is the first
derivative of another

00:01:58.050 --> 00:02:01.610
function, we'll say dw dx.

00:02:01.610 --> 00:02:03.750
And the reason I'm going to do
that is so we're not too

00:02:03.750 --> 00:02:06.630
nervous about how we
solve this problem.

00:02:06.630 --> 00:02:08.800
So let's just assume that.

00:02:08.800 --> 00:02:11.480
So I'm introducing another
function, w, which is the

00:02:11.480 --> 00:02:15.980
first derivative of y with
respect to x, ultimately.

00:02:15.980 --> 00:02:19.010
Because its derivative is the
second derivative of y with

00:02:19.010 --> 00:02:20.130
respect to x.

00:02:20.130 --> 00:02:23.580
So let's see how to solve the
differential equation

00:02:23.580 --> 00:02:27.040
dw dx equals 6x.

00:02:27.040 --> 00:02:28.870
Now you may be able to
do that right away.

00:02:28.870 --> 00:02:30.100
You may see what this
is right away.

00:02:30.100 --> 00:02:31.380
If you're a little nervous,
we can do a

00:02:31.380 --> 00:02:33.050
separation of variables.

00:02:33.050 --> 00:02:36.796
So right away, maybe some of you
can see that this will be

00:02:36.796 --> 00:02:38.730
2x-- sorry--

00:02:38.730 --> 00:02:40.430
3x squared.

00:02:40.430 --> 00:02:42.100
But let's just double-check.

00:02:42.100 --> 00:02:44.770
So, separation of variables,
on this side we get the

00:02:44.770 --> 00:02:45.810
integral of dw.

00:02:45.810 --> 00:02:48.000
On this side we get the
integral of 6x dx.

00:02:50.590 --> 00:02:53.480
Here we get a w.

00:02:53.480 --> 00:02:58.530
And here, again we get, we
should really do 6x squared

00:02:58.530 --> 00:03:01.740
over 2 plus a constant.

00:03:01.740 --> 00:03:07.060
So that's 3x squared
plus a constant.

00:03:07.060 --> 00:03:11.410
I'm going to write c1 here
because we're went to need a

00:03:11.410 --> 00:03:12.990
little bit of information.

00:03:12.990 --> 00:03:15.370
We're going to need another
constant later.

00:03:15.370 --> 00:03:19.370
So we actually now know
the derivative of y

00:03:19.370 --> 00:03:20.360
with respect to x.

00:03:20.360 --> 00:03:27.360
What we found here, I'll just
write that in, is dy dx.

00:03:27.360 --> 00:03:28.290
Again, let me remind you why.

00:03:28.290 --> 00:03:32.670
We had, we were saying the
second derivative of y with

00:03:32.670 --> 00:03:36.170
respect to x we're going
to call dw dx.

00:03:36.170 --> 00:03:42.200
So when I took an integral
of dw dx, I got w.

00:03:42.200 --> 00:03:44.840
So that means I've taken one
antiderivative here and so now

00:03:44.840 --> 00:03:46.120
I have dy dx.

00:03:46.120 --> 00:03:48.241
So this is dy dx.

00:03:48.241 --> 00:03:50.830
I'm going to draw a line and
now we want to find y.

00:03:50.830 --> 00:03:53.250
And again we can use separation
of variables.

00:03:53.250 --> 00:03:56.750
Or this time I'm just going
to do the problem without

00:03:56.750 --> 00:03:59.990
separating variables, because
I actually know what an

00:03:59.990 --> 00:04:02.530
antiderivative is of this, what
an antiderivative is of

00:04:02.530 --> 00:04:05.150
this, and then I need to
add one more constant.

00:04:05.150 --> 00:04:10.340
So I can say that y is
definitely equal to x cubed

00:04:10.340 --> 00:04:14.600
plus c1 x plus c2.

00:04:14.600 --> 00:04:17.315
And let me just again, let's
see why that is.

00:04:17.315 --> 00:04:18.330
Right?

00:04:18.330 --> 00:04:22.840
This antiderivative of
this is x cubed.

00:04:22.840 --> 00:04:26.340
Antiderivative of this is,
it's a constant so its

00:04:26.340 --> 00:04:29.130
antiderivative is c1 times x.

00:04:29.130 --> 00:04:31.270
And then I have to add on
another constant because I

00:04:31.270 --> 00:04:34.510
have a whole family of
possible solutions.

00:04:34.510 --> 00:04:35.990
So here I have y.

00:04:35.990 --> 00:04:39.850
And now I need to figure out
how to use number two.

00:04:39.850 --> 00:04:42.110
Maybe before you even go on, you
want to check, does this

00:04:42.110 --> 00:04:44.700
really satisfy number one?

00:04:44.700 --> 00:04:47.300
So if we wanted to check that,
we just take two derivatives

00:04:47.300 --> 00:04:49.460
of this expression on
the right-hand side.

00:04:49.460 --> 00:04:51.570
Two derivatives of this is 0.

00:04:51.570 --> 00:04:53.370
Two derivative of this is 0.

00:04:53.370 --> 00:04:55.240
And two derivatives
of this is 6x.

00:04:55.240 --> 00:04:57.600
So I do indeed get
what I want.

00:04:57.600 --> 00:04:59.480
So now we definitely can
go on to number 2.

00:04:59.480 --> 00:05:01.270
OK?

00:05:01.270 --> 00:05:02.460
So, what do we have
number two?

00:05:02.460 --> 00:05:04.510
It says we have some initial
conditions here.

00:05:04.510 --> 00:05:07.510
The graph in the x y plane
passes through the point 1,1

00:05:07.510 --> 00:05:10.550
and it has a horizontal
tangent there.

00:05:10.550 --> 00:05:11.960
Now what does that
actually mean?

00:05:11.960 --> 00:05:12.790
Let's think about that.

00:05:12.790 --> 00:05:21.215
That actually means that two
says f of 1 equals 1.

00:05:21.215 --> 00:05:22.970
Right?

00:05:22.970 --> 00:05:24.410
y is equal to f of x.

00:05:24.410 --> 00:05:27.060
So we can write this
also as f of x.

00:05:27.060 --> 00:05:30.530
So two, the first part says
that f of 1 is 1.

00:05:30.530 --> 00:05:31.910
And what does this
second condition?

00:05:31.910 --> 00:05:33.080
Let's check this second
condition.

00:05:33.080 --> 00:05:35.670
It says it has a horizontal
tangent there.

00:05:35.670 --> 00:05:38.820
Horizontal tangent means
that its derivative at

00:05:38.820 --> 00:05:41.040
that x value is 0.

00:05:41.040 --> 00:05:43.790
So let me write down that
in a nice form.

00:05:43.790 --> 00:05:48.190
The derivative at that x
value is equal to 0.

00:05:48.190 --> 00:05:49.970
This is a little different,
maybe, from what we've seen

00:05:49.970 --> 00:05:50.610
previously.

00:05:50.610 --> 00:05:53.970
In the lecture you saw examples,
at least certainly,

00:05:53.970 --> 00:05:55.760
where you had one initial
condition.

00:05:55.760 --> 00:05:57.460
Here we need two initial
conditions.

00:05:57.460 --> 00:06:00.450
And you see why, is because we
actually have two constants.

00:06:00.450 --> 00:06:01.630
Where did that come from?

00:06:01.630 --> 00:06:04.010
It's because we started with a
second derivative instead of

00:06:04.010 --> 00:06:05.370
just the first derivative.

00:06:05.370 --> 00:06:07.650
So that's kind of, that's
why you see more initial

00:06:07.650 --> 00:06:11.330
conditions than maybe you've
seen previously.

00:06:11.330 --> 00:06:13.570
So, let's plug these in and
let's see what we get.

00:06:13.570 --> 00:06:17.400
If f of 1 equals 1, then
let's evaluate that.

00:06:17.400 --> 00:06:23.705
f of 1 is equal to 1 cubed plus
1 times c1 plus 1 times,

00:06:23.705 --> 00:06:23.955
or just 1, or c2 there--
sorry, there's no x

00:06:23.955 --> 00:06:25.205
there, so just c2.

00:06:30.780 --> 00:06:33.810
And that all has to equal 1.

00:06:33.810 --> 00:06:35.370
And then let's look at what
the derivative is.

00:06:35.370 --> 00:06:38.520
The derivative is
still over here.

00:06:38.520 --> 00:06:43.500
So f prime at 1 is equal to
3 times 1 squared, so 3

00:06:43.500 --> 00:06:46.880
times 1, plus c1.

00:06:46.880 --> 00:06:51.410
And the condition says that
equals 0, equals 0.

00:06:51.410 --> 00:06:52.490
So we can read off.

00:06:52.490 --> 00:06:54.990
The nice thing is this is system
of equations but one of

00:06:54.990 --> 00:06:57.400
them is very easy to solve
initially, then we can

00:06:57.400 --> 00:06:58.460
substitute.

00:06:58.460 --> 00:06:59.420
So what does this say?

00:06:59.420 --> 00:07:01.990
Well 3 plus c1 equals 0.

00:07:01.990 --> 00:07:06.660
So c1 is equal to minus
3, negative 3.

00:07:06.660 --> 00:07:10.411
If I plug in negative 3 for
c1, in this expression, in

00:07:10.411 --> 00:07:15.230
this equation up here, I get
negative 3 plus 1 plus c2 has

00:07:15.230 --> 00:07:16.910
to equal 1.

00:07:16.910 --> 00:07:19.510
If I subtract the 1's from both
sides I get negative 3

00:07:19.510 --> 00:07:21.580
plus c2 has to equal 0.

00:07:21.580 --> 00:07:25.610
So c2 has to actually equal 3.

00:07:25.610 --> 00:07:32.430
So the final, final answer is
evaluating, or plugging in the

00:07:32.430 --> 00:07:35.150
c1 and the c2 in for the
constants there.

00:07:35.150 --> 00:07:42.820
The final, final answer is
x cubed minus 3x plus 3.

00:07:46.270 --> 00:07:49.290
So we started with a
differential equation and two

00:07:49.290 --> 00:07:50.720
sets of initial conditions.

00:07:50.720 --> 00:07:54.690
And we came up with one solution
that satisfies that.

00:07:54.690 --> 00:07:57.410
Now you can look at this, you
could graph this on a

00:07:57.410 --> 00:08:00.770
calculator or computer and look
and see if it satisfies

00:08:00.770 --> 00:08:04.780
that it actually passes through
the point 1,1 and has

00:08:04.780 --> 00:08:06.250
a horizontal tangent there.

00:08:06.250 --> 00:08:08.840
But we know, based on our
work, that that actually

00:08:08.840 --> 00:08:10.230
should happen.

00:08:10.230 --> 00:08:13.140
So I think that's
where I'll stop.